SIMPLE: injunction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Injunction
<hw>In*junc"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>injunctio</ets>, fr. <ets>injungere</ets>, <ets>injunctum</ets>, to
join into, to enjoin. See <er>Enjoin</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of enjoining; the act of directing, commanding, or
prohibiting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is enjoined; an order; a mandate; a
decree; a command; a precept; a direction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For still they knew, and ought to have still remembered,⟦br⟧
The high <qex>injunction</qex>, not to taste that fruit.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Necessary as the <qex>injunctions</qex> of lawful authority.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A writ or process, granted by a
court of equity, and, in some cases, under statutes, by a court of law,
whereby a party is required to do or to refrain from doing certain acts,
according to the exigency of the writ.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ It is more generally used as a preventive than as a
restorative process, although by no means confined to the former.</note>
<rj><au>Wharton.</au> <au>Daniell.</au> <au>Story.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Injure</ent>⟦br⟧
